notes.note:
From: Emenike Eziukwu <emenike_eziukwu@yahoo.com>
Sent: Sunday, April 2, 2023 8:10 AM
To: claims <claims@canadageneral.ca>
Cc: Mark instantwheels.ca <mark@instantwheels.ca>; Ngozi Eziukwu <ngozi.eziukwu@yahoo.com>
Subject: Warranty Claim Case_W-184637
 
Hello Warranty Claims team, 
The review of the claim on Ford Escape 2015 which I have been told is denied twice is a major cause of concern for my family. We purchased the vehicle from the dealership alongside with a warranty cover because we wanted some level of confidence going forward. Apparently it appears that the decision to deny claim was based off our statement over the telephone with the Warranty Company Reps.

I am taking this moment to put in writing a sequence of events and to seek redress on the decision; as well as to understand what is left on this Warranty cover (Contract No: W-184637)?

Car was purchased and taken out of dealership on Dec 08, 2022 in good working condition. Check engine light came on the dash Dec 10th (Saturday) and was taken to dealership Dec 12th for spot scan-check. Alarm was cleared as spurious and car drives well. Alarm came on again Dec 13th but later cleared off. A follow up scan at dealership showed O2 sensor, which was attributed to weather fluctuations. With understanding that the alarm was not a cause of concern, Dealership was willing to make a mechanic appointment for thorough diagnostics if check engine light keeps coming on intermittently. However, all along the car drives well, the other concern which we established was that when we start the car in the morning, the exhaust fumes were quite choking, this was attributed to the closed garage parking position.

On Jan 03, 2023 evening while driving, check engine light flashed and high engine temperature alarm came on, I immediately pulled car over, turned ignition off and allowed engine to cool and drove car home. Reported issue to dealership and was asked to come over by next available business day. On Jan 4th morning, checked and saw that the coolant reservoir was empty, topped up with bottled water after consultation call to Dealership. Visited dealership Jan 9th, at this point, the mechanic appointment was urgent, as we have to keep topping up coolant.
Jan 19th visited Mechanic shop (Wicket & Wrench) to check car problem. A follow up appointment on Jan 27th was necessary to complete diagnostics on problem. But Repair required Warranty claim authorization which was not sorted till I have to travel out of Canada Feb 5th. Subsequently Wicket & Wrench reached my wife to announce that the repair will no more be through their shop but a new shop approved by Warranty company. My wife called the Canada General Warranty contact number and the claims agent asked that the car be taken to Jensen’s shop (Prospect street) for diagnostic check. With the completion of Jensen’s check and request for repair authorization, the news of denial was passed on which we could not comprehend having done everything in good faith.
The Dealer said that he completed the presale checks on the car before it was sold to us. We do not understand how this is determined as pre-existing problem and requiring us to make unplanned huge financial expense to bear cost of repair. Does it mean the Warranty contract is voided or there is something required of us to help the case?
I await your kind response.
Regards,
Emenike Eziukwu

notes.note:
Customer emailed:
I was having issues starting my car and need to have it repaired. I purchased your Principal 36 month/60,000 km protection in Dec 2022 at Janex Auto Sales in Ottawa, Ontario. My plate number is CXHC391 and VIN KM8J3CA4XJU639068 I would like to know what coverage I have for repairs? What is the authorized locations that I should bring the car to? Thanks, Richard Ouellette

I replied:
Thanks for your email.
The warranty you have is the Principal Warranty. It is a powertrain warranty that covers the internally lubricated parts of your engine, transmission, differential, transfer case and turbo charger, as listed on your warranty contract.
The Canada General authorized repair facilities can be found on our website. Log onto canadageneral.ca then click on Contact Us.
There you will find a map with all of our authorized repair facilities, highlighted with blue pointers.

Best Regards,
Adam Halko
Claims Manager
